47. Configure entities for REST and GraphQL, including data caching,
pagination, searching, and filtering
• Click “Try it out” to enter values.
• You can use:
o $select to select the fields (columns) to be returned.
o For example, AddressLine1,City
o $filter it using OData predicates:
o eq = equals,
o ne = not equals to,
o and = both conditions need to be true,
o or = either condition can be true,
o gt = greater than,
o lt = less than.
 47. Configure entities for REST and GraphQL, including data caching, pagination,
searching, and filtering

o For example, AddressID gt 25
o http://localhost:5000/api/Address?$filter=AddressID eq 25
o http://localhost:5000/api/Address?$filter=AddressID gt 25
o $orderby to sort
o For example, AddressID desc
• You can also get a page of data by using first (page size) and after (the
previous page)
o http://localhost:5000/api/Address?$first=10
o If it ends with
"nextLink":http://localhost:5000/api/Address?$first=10&$after=AB
CD then you can use:
o http://localhost:5000/api/Address?$first=10&$after=ABCD
to connect to the next page.
• http://localhost:5000/graphql when mode is “development” (this uses
GraphiQL UI). In “production”, this testbed is not used, but you can use
Postman Desktop Agent. You can run queries like:
query AddressList {
 addresses
 { items
 { AddressID, City}}
}
• in items, you can choose which columns to return
• for example { column1 column2 } (no commas)
• there is no * wildcard equivalent – you do need to state each field.
• You can alias fields, such as bookTitle: title takes the “title” column and
renames it as “bookTitle”.
• You can also have additional tables in items – this does an INNER JOIN –
for example { column1 column2 different_table {column3 column4 } }
• in filter, you can reduce the number of rows using OData predicates:
• eq/neq – equal/not equal. For example:
 47. Configure entities for REST and GraphQL, including data caching, pagination,
searching, and filtering

o column1 {eq: 5},
o column2 {neq: "Foundation"}
• gt/gte – greater [or equal to]
• lt/lte – less than [or equal to]
• and/or. For example:
o or: [ {column1 {eq: 5} }, { column2 {neq: "Foundation"} } ]
• contains/notContains – anywhere within a string
• startsWith/endsWith – at the beginning/end of a string
• in. For example:
o (filter: { category: { in: [“Foundation”, “Advanced”] } } )
• isNull. For example:
o (filter: { category: { isNull: false } } )
• groupBy combines by a particular field(s). For example:
• groupBy: { fields: ["column1“] }
• orderBy orders the query before using first or after.
• By default, DAB will sort ascending by the primary key.
• You can order by DESC or ASC.
• For example: books(orderBy: { year: DESC, title: ASC }, first: 5) { items { id
title year } }
• first allows you to return a specified number of rows (in a page).
• The default page is 100,
• The maximum page size defaults to 100,000.
• For example: books(first: 5)
• after allows you to take the end of a previous page, and continue it.
• You can add in a query:
o hasNextPage – to find out whether additional data exists, and
o endCursor – to get the next token.
• You might get the response
 47. Configure entities for REST and GraphQL, including data caching, pagination,
searching, and filtering

o { "data" : { … "hasNextPage" : true, "endCursor": "ABCDE“ } }
• then you can use, in the next query.
o query { books(first: 3, after: "ABCDE") { items { … } } }
• aggregates allows you to do a sum, average, min, max and/or count.
• For example:
{ book { items { … }
aggregates { column1 { sum average min max } } } }
• You can also use “distinct: true” for count, and “having: { }” to filter after
aggregation.
• You can use:
o totalcost: sum (totalcost becomes an alias),
o sum(having: {gt: 10000 } ) , and
o count(distinct: true)
• Additional query/stored procedures to add:
dab add CustomerAndAddress --source SalesLT.vCustomerAndAddress --source.keyfields CustomerID --permissions "anonymous:read"
• Create Stored Procedure:
CREATE PROC SalesLT.Product700 AS
select *
from SalesLT.Product
WHERE ProductID BETWEEN 700 AND 799;
